The theory of executive severance goes something like this. The chief execu=
tive officer of a public company wants to run the company. Running the comp=
any pays well, it=E2=80=99s prestigious, it makes the CEO feel powerful and=
 important. Also the CEO has probably devoted much of her career to the com=
pany, cares about it, and has strong views on how it should be run; she=E2=
=80=99d be sad if someone else took it over and ran it differently.
But the CEO does not, in the general case,=C2=A0own=C2=A0the company. The c=
ompany does not belong to her. She works for the shareholders=C2=A0and has =
a fiduciary duty to do what is in their best interests. Sometimes, it is go=
od for the shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0though bad for the CEO =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0to let someone else take over the company. In particular, sometimes publ=
ic companies get hostile takeover bids: Somebody else offers to buy all the=
 stock, for cash, at a premium to the current stock price. Sometimes this i=
s bad for shareholders (the company is worth more in the long run, on its o=
wn, with current management, than the hostile bidder is willing to pay), bu=
t sometimes it is good: The hostile bidder might be willing to pay more for=
 the company than it is worth under current management.=C2=A0
In that case, shareholders want the CEO to say =E2=80=9Cyep, this bid is go=
od, we should let the hostile bidder run the company and cash out sharehold=
ers, I will step aside, it=E2=80=99s been fun.=E2=80=9D But of course the C=
EO might not=C2=A0want=C2=A0to step aside. She wants to run the company, fo=
r all the reasons I said above, plus the hostile bidder is hostile: Probabl=
y the hostile bidder has=C2=A0said rude things=C2=A0about the CEO and has=
=C2=A0plans for the company she dislikes. She might want to say no to the b=
idder.
The CEO of a public company can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0completely=C2=A0prevent a ho=
stile bidder from acquiring the company =E2=80=94=C2=A0if the shareholders =
want the deal, ultimately the hostile bidder can probably launch a tender o=
ffer and a proxy fight and get the company over the CEO=E2=80=99s and the b=
oard=E2=80=99s objections =E2=80=94=C2=A0but she can certainly delay and co=
mplicate the process. In practice, the chances of a deal getting done are m=
uch worse if the CEO adamantly opposes it.=C2=A0
Corporate governance theory and practice have=C2=A0a solution to this probl=
em, which is: Promise the CEO a giant bag of money for walking away. Put a =
provision in her employment contract saying that, if someone else takes ove=
r the company and she leaves,
  [1]
=C2=A0she gets paid a lot of money, probably a multiple of her salary. Hand=
ing over the company to a hostile bidder is bad for her in a lot of ways (l=
ess prestige, handing her beloved company to a rude interloper) but, with t=
he severance package, it is also=C2=A0good=C2=A0for her in some other impor=
tant ways (bag of money, doesn=E2=80=99t have to come to the office anymore=
).
When Elon Musk   launched his bid to buy Twitter Inc. in April 2022, I am f=
airly certain that Twitter=E2=80=99s CEO, Parag Agrawal, rolled his eyes an=
d wished Musk would go away. Agrawal had spent most of his career at Twitte=
r, had fairly recently been promoted to the top job, was  getting paid mill=
ions of dollars a year and presumably didn=E2=80=99t want to be kicked out =
(or start answering to Musk). Also Musk was=C2=A0quite rude to, and about,=
=C2=A0him, tweeting mean things about Twitter and texting Agrawal=C2=A0huff=
ily to say =E2=80=9Cwhat did you get done this week=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ct=
his is a waste of time.=E2=80=9D
But Musk offered to pay $54.20 per share, in cash, for Twitter, which was s=
ignificantly higher than the stock price at the time. Agrawal could have sa=
id =E2=80=9Cno, no, we have a long-term value creation plan that will be wo=
rth far more than $54.20 per share, so we must fight off Elon Musk and pres=
erve the company=E2=80=99s independence, for shareholders.=E2=80=9D Perhaps=
, as CEO, he could have persuaded the board of directors to back that appro=
ach. Perhaps he could have sold that plan to shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0or=
 perhaps he could have just used a   poison pill and other takeover-defense=
 tools to frustrate Musk as much as possible.
Perhaps that would have=C2=A0worked: Perhaps Agrawal could have slowed down=
 the deal process enough that Musk would change his mind, either because he=
 generally has a short attention span or because social-media company valua=
tions fell in the spring of 2022 and his bid for Twitter quickly became a b=
ad idea. That would have been good for Agrawal: He could have kept running =
the company, getting paid and having a nice time. It would have been=C2=A0v=
ery bad=C2=A0for Twitter shareholders: They would have missed out on $54.20=
 per share, and they=E2=80=99d be stuck holding Twitter stock as social-med=
ia valuations fell.
But, nope: Agrawal and Twitter=E2=80=99s board   rapidly capitulated, with =
Agrawal giving employees a pretty unstirring speech about how the board had=
 no choice but to take the best deal for shareholders. So they signed a mer=
ger agreement to sell the company to Musk for $54.20 per share.
And then Musk tried to get out of it! A few months later, after social-medi=
a valuations=C2=A0did=C2=A0fall, Musk=C2=A0did=C2=A0change his mind, and he=
 sent Twitter a letter   saying he was terminating the deal! Which would ha=
ve been a catastrophe for Twitter shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0who would be =
stuck holding Twitter stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0but would have been =E2=80=A6=C2=
=A0kind of nice for Agrawal? Keep his job, keep his paycheck, keep running =
Twitter, get a chance to turn things around without meddling from Musk?
He could have done that! He could have sent Musk back a letter saying =E2=
=80=9Csorry you feel that way Elon, but we=E2=80=99d never force you to clo=
se a deal you don=E2=80=99t want to close, so, bye.=E2=80=9D
  [2]
 Move on with his life, as Twitter CEO.
But, nope again:=C2=A0Agrawal, and Twitter=E2=80=99s board and executive te=
am, hired lawyers and sued Musk and argued that he had to close the deal, a=
nd=20
of course they were right, and ultimately Musk gave up and closed the deal.=
 And Twitter=E2=80=99s shareholders got their $54.20, which was a great res=
ult for them under the circumstances. And Agrawal and his executive team go=
t fired, which was an=C2=A0absolutely inevitable=C2=A0result for them under=
 the circumstances: They were the executives of the target in a hostile tak=
eover, so they were going to get fired anyway, but also they ramped up the =
hostility of the takeover by=C2=A0suing the acquirer to force him to close,=
 so of course they got=C2=A0extra=C2=A0fired.=C2=A0Musk was mad at them! Fo=
r making him buy Twitter!
My point here is that few CEOs have ever deserved their severance package m=
ore than Parag Agrawal. This is not a commentary on his performance running=
 Twitter:=C2=A0That=C2=A0performance was, you know, bad enough that Elon Mu=
sk bought the company. But a severance package is not a reward for good per=
formance as CEO! A severance package is a reward for=C2=A0getting out of th=
e way=C2=A0and letting someone else take over. And few CEOs have worked har=
der, or had a more unpleasant time, getting out of the way. He earned his m=
illions.
But then Musk didn=E2=80=99t pay him,   so he=E2=80=99s suing:

Four ex-Twitter executives, including former Chief Executive Officer Parag =
Agrawal, sued company owner Elon Musk for allegedly stiffing them on more t=
han $128 million in severance payments after they were ousted from the comp=
any.
The former top officials said Musk showed =E2=80=9Cspecial ire=E2=80=9D tow=
ard them after he took over the social-media platform in 2022, publicly vow=
ing to withhold their severance to recoup about $200 million from the $44 b=
illion deal, according to a lawsuit filed Monday in federal court in northe=
rn California.
Twitter, which Musk renamed X, has been accused in multiple suits of numero=
us labor and workplace violations, including failing to pay severance to th=
ousands of workers laid off in the months after the takeover. The company a=
lso was accused in a raft of suits of failing to pay millions owed to vendo=
rs and landlords while purportedly trying to stay financially solvent.
=E2=80=9CUnder Musk=E2=80=99s control, Twitter has become a scofflaw, stiff=
ing employees, landlords, vendors, and others. Musk doesn=E2=80=99t pay his=
 bills, believes the rules don=E2=80=99t apply to him, and uses his wealth =
and power to run roughshod over anyone who disagrees with him,=E2=80=9D law=
yers for Agrawal and the other ex-executives said in the 38-page complaint.

Here is  the complaint. Agrawal and the other executives =E2=80=94=C2=A0for=
mer Chief Financial Officer Ned Segal, Chief Legal Officer Vijaya Gadde and=
 General Counsel Sean Edgett =E2=80=94=C2=A0had severance deals entitling t=
hem to get paid if Twitter was taken over and they were terminated =E2=80=
=9Cwithout cause.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9C=E2=80=98Cause=E2=80=99=C2=A0under the =
severance plans is limited to extremely narrow circumstances, such as being=
 convicted of a felony or committing =E2=80=98gross negligence=E2=80=99=C2=
=A0or =E2=80=98willful misconduct.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D Musk fired them immedi=
ately after the takeover =E2=80=94=C2=A0racing to fire them before they cou=
ld resign and get severance =E2=80=94=C2=A0and claimed it was for =E2=80=9C=
cause.=E2=80=9D The supposed =E2=80=9Ccause=E2=80=9D was things like the ex=
ecutives paying lawyers to sue Musk to make him close the deal, which Musk =
argued was a waste of corporate resources. That is not how severance is sup=
posed to work! The complaint says:
Severance plans are an important feature of modern corporate governance, al=
igning the economic interests of executives and shareholders in the face of=
 a corporate takeover, especially one as contentious as Musk=E2=80=99s acqu=
isition of Twitter. Severance plans encourage=C2=A0everyone to work toward =
getting the deal done. For example, without severance plans, executives cou=
ld have a financial incentive to oppose an acquisition even when that acqui=
sition is in the best interests of shareholders. Executives could also have=
 a professional incentive to leave the company before the closing, which co=
uld jeopardize the company=E2=80=99s ability to close the transaction and t=
he public shareholders=E2=80=99 ability to get the control premium provided=
 by the acquisition. Executives=E2=80=99 severance benefits are designed to=
 be legally resilient, as they must be, because severance payments are nece=
ssarily made by the acquired entity only after it passes into the hands of =
its acquiror. If executives could not count on getting their contractual se=
verance, they would have no incentive to stay through the acquisition to ru=
n the business, oversee the acquisition process, and make sure the sharehol=
ders get paid.
The problem is that Twitter=E2=80=99s old executives were working on behalf=
 of its old public shareholders, and they got a good deal for those shareho=
lders. But to do that, they had to work=C2=A0against=C2=A0its new owner, Mu=
sk, so they got=C2=A0him=C2=A0a bad deal. And the public shareholders agree=
d to the severance package, but Musk has to pay it. Of course he doesn=E2=
=80=99t want to!

