      Oh Elon (2)
   =20
 =20

Elsewhere in Twitter/X and   its=C2=A0bills:

A bank group spearheaded by Morgan Stanley held discussions with Elon Musk =
and his team about refinancing a roughly $12.5 billion debt package that su=
pported the tech billionaire=E2=80=99s take-private of the social media pla=
tform X, according to people with knowledge of the matter.
In talks that faltered earlier this year, certain banks and Musk=E2=80=99s =
team explored options to strengthen the debt package, said the people, who =
asked not to be identified discussing confidential talks. The parties discu=
ssed options that could reduce the cost of the debt and make it less risky =
for banks to hold, one of the people said.
A group of seven banks, led by the New York-based lender, has been stuck ho=
lding the debt since 2022. They=E2=80=99ve repeatedly renewed an agreement =
not to individually offload their holdings, with the goal of coordinating a=
 sale when X =E2=80=94 formerly known as Twitter =E2=80=94 is on firmer fin=
ancial footing with stable advertising revenues, subscription growth and fu=
rther traction from a planned peer-to-peer payments platform, one of the pe=
ople said.

Hmm.=C2=A0=E2=80=9COptions that could reduce the cost of the debt and make =
it less risky for banks to hold.=E2=80=9D What do you think that means? Her=
e=E2=80=99s one possibility: If you have debt that pays very high interest =
and makes your lenders nervous, there is a potential win-win transaction in=
 which you put up more collateral (making the debt safer) and the banks cut=
 the interest rate (to reflect its increased safety and to compensate you f=
or encumbering collateral).
Here I am not particularly convinced that X has much in the way of collater=
al that could improve the profile of this debt. But =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I mean =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0Elon Musk=C2=A0does? Like, obviously? Like if he were to ple=
dge $12.5 billion =E2=80=94=C2=A0or $25 billion, or frankly $5 billion =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0of Tesla Inc. stock to these lenders, that would make them a=C2=
=A0lot=C2=A0more comfortable=C2=A0and probably buy down his interest rate. =
Or if he were to co-sign the debt =E2=80=94=C2=A0if he agreed to guarantee =
or be a co-obligor on it, with recourse to him =E2=80=94=C2=A0then, fine, i=
nvestment-grade rating and lower interest payments.
  [3]
 =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a win-win Elon, you get a lower interest rate just f=
or signing your name here!=E2=80=9D He=E2=80=99s not gonna fall for that, b=
ut it was worth a shot for the banks.

 =20
   =20
      Vote-buying
   =20
 =20

There is a three-way proxy fight going on at Walt Disney Co. Nelson Peltz=
=E2=80=99s Trian Fund Management LP has nominated two candidates for Disney=
=E2=80=99s board of directors, Blackwells Capital LLC has nominated three o=
ther candidates=C2=A0and=C2=A0Disney opposes all of them. There are competi=
ng websites. Blackwells owns about 157,000=C2=A0shares of Disney stock (abo=
ut $17.9 million worth), or about 0.0086% of the 1.8 billion shares outstan=
ding. Trian=E2=80=99s group=C2=A0owns=C2=A0about 32.3 million shares ($3.7 =
billion), or about 1.76% of the stock.
  [4]
 Disney Chief Executive Officer Robert Iger owns about 205,000 shares ($23 =
million, 0.011%), plus another 2.2 million shares=E2=80=99 worth of options=
. The biggest shareholders are the usual =E2=80=9CBig Three=E2=80=9D index =
fund firms (Vanguard, BlackRock, State Street).
So=C2=A0lot of votes are up for grabs: This is not a proxy fight between an=
 activist with a big stake and a CEO with a big stake, where each side alre=
ady owns a lot of shares, but a battle of persuasion where three smallish s=
hareholders will try to get the rest of the shareholders to vote for their =
platforms.
And then there=E2=80=99s this:

Mom-and-pop investors are also being courted for their votes on a new marke=
tplace called Shareholder Vote [Exchange], which runs auctions for sharehol=
ders' proxy votes. Disney is unusual because individual investors own more =
than one-third of Disney's 1.8 billion shares, more than the typical compan=
y,=C2=A0per The Wall Street Journal.
A bidder on Shareholder Vote [Exchange] is offering as much as $100,000 for=
 500,000 proxy votes, or 20 cents per vote, the most the site has seen sinc=
e its=C2=A0launch two years ago, said cofounder and COO Steven Xu.
Xu said Shareholder Vote [Exchange] doesn't reveal the names of the bidders=
 but confirmed the bid is from a current shareholder. Trian and Blackwell d=
idn't immediately respond to requests for comment from Business Insider abo=
ut if they're the bidder in question.

Here=E2=80=99s the web page for the auction. As of today I see a bid of $10=
0,000 for 500,000 votes, and 12,417 votes listed for sale. So the market is=
 not particularly close to clearing. Also, if you bought 500,000 votes, tha=
t would get you 0.027% of the votes, which, I mean,=C2=A0maybe=C2=A0that wi=
ll make the difference between getting your nominee elected and not?
Ehh. I don=E2=80=99t see it. We have talked about the Shareholder Vote Exch=
ange a  couple of  times=C2=A0before. It=E2=80=99s fun! Why not. The idea o=
f being able to sell shareholder votes is clearly icky to some people; I th=
ink it is, like,=C2=A0morally=C2=A0fine but mechanically and legally messy.=
=C2=A0I wrote:
Surely the real high-dollar case for buying shareholder votes is in=C2=A0co=
ntested proxy fights, where some activist investor has millions of dollars =
on the line and wants to get its own slate of directors elected. (Also in c=
ontested takeovers.) And there I just have trouble imagining big activist s=
hareholders buying votes in proxy fights this way, in part because the disc=
losure and reputational issues seem like they=E2=80=99d be a mess. The dist=
inguishing feature of proxy fights and hostile takeovers is that everyone s=
ues everyone else about everything, and also =E2=80=9Cbedbugs=E2=80=9D them=
 to the US Securities and Exchange Commission, calling up the SEC to say =
=E2=80=9Chey did you notice our opponents doing something illegal?=E2=80=9D=
 Can you imagine the hay that some corporate managers would make out of an =
evil activist hedge fund=C2=A0buying votes?
And, sure, if you buy 10% of the vote for 20 cents per share (the stock clo=
sed yesterday at $113.69), that=E2=80=99s going to go to court. If you bid =
20 cents per share for 0.027% of the votes =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I think no one wi=
ll care? This is good publicity for Shareholder Vote Exchange, but I=E2=80=
=99m not sure it=E2=80=99s anything more than that.

