<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The theory of executive severance goes somethi=
ng like this. The chief executive officer of a public company wants to run =
the company. Running the company pays well, it=E2=80=99s prestigious, it ma=
kes the CEO feel powerful and important. Also the CEO has probably devoted =
much of her career to the company, cares about it, and has strong views on =
how it should be run; she=E2=80=99d be sad if someone else took it over and=
 ran it differently.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the CEO does not, in the general case,=C2=
=A0<em>own=C2=A0</em>the company. The company does not belong to her. She w=
orks for the shareholders=C2=A0and has a fiduciary duty to do what is in th=
eir best interests. Sometimes, it is good for the shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0though bad for the CEO =E2=80=94=C2=A0to let someone else take over the =
company. In particular, sometimes public companies get hostile takeover bid=
s: Somebody else offers to buy all the stock, for cash, at a premium to the=
 current stock price. Sometimes this is bad for shareholders (the company i=
s worth more in the long run, on its own, with current management, than the=
 hostile bidder is willing to pay), but sometimes it is good: The hostile b=
idder might be willing to pay more for the company than it is worth under c=
urrent management.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In that case, shareholders want the CEO to say=
 =E2=80=9Cyep, this bid is good, we should let the hostile bidder run the c=
ompany and cash out shareholders, I will step aside, it=E2=80=99s been fun.=
=E2=80=9D But of course the CEO might not=C2=A0<em>want=C2=A0</em>to step a=
side. She wants to run the company, for all the reasons I said above, plus =
the hostile bidder is <em>hostile</em>: Probably the hostile bidder has=C2=
=A0<em>said rude things=C2=A0</em>about the CEO and has=C2=A0<em>plans for =
the company she dislikes</em>. She might want to say no to the bidder.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The CEO of a public company can=E2=80=99t=C2=
=A0<em>completely=C2=A0</em>prevent a hostile bidder from acquiring the com=
pany =E2=80=94=C2=A0if the shareholders want the deal, ultimately the hosti=
le bidder can probably launch a tender offer and a proxy fight and get the =
company over the CEO=E2=80=99s and the board=E2=80=99s objections =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0but she can certainly delay and complicate the process. In practice, =
the chances of a deal getting done are much worse if the CEO adamantly oppo=
ses it.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Corporate governance theory and practice have=
=C2=A0a solution to this problem, which is: Promise the CEO a giant bag of =
money for walking away. Put a provision in her employment contract saying t=
hat, if someone else takes over the company and she leaves,<a class=3D"foot=
note-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importan=
t; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0she gets paid a lot of money, probably a multiple of her salary. =
Handing over the company to a hostile bidder is bad for her in a lot of way=
s (less prestige, handing her beloved company to a rude interloper) but, wi=
th the severance package, it is also=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>for her in som=
e other important ways (bag of money, doesn=E2=80=99t have to come to the o=
ffice anymore).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When Elon Musk <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/34575923.258370/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
S9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMTUvc3VyZS1lbG9uLW11c2stbWlnaHQtYnV5LXR3=
aXR0ZXI_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMwNTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc29=
1cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMzA1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB63aac333" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  launched his bid</a> to buy Twi=
tter Inc. in April 2022, I am fairly certain that Twitter=E2=80=99s CEO, Pa=
rag Agrawal, rolled his eyes and wished Musk would go away. Agrawal had spe=
nt most of his career at Twitter, had fairly recently been promoted to the =
top job, was <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34575=
923.258370/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTgwOTEv=
MDAwMTE0MDM2MTIyMDE0MDQ5L255MjAwMDE5MjF4M19kZWYxNGEuaHRtI3RFQw/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB398d0f6e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;"> getting paid</a> millions of dollars a year=
 and presumably didn=E2=80=99t want to be kicked out (or start answering to=
 Musk). Also Musk <em>was=C2=A0</em>quite rude to, and about,=C2=A0him, twe=
eting mean things about Twitter and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/34575923.258370/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlZ3VhcmRpYW4uY29tL3RlY=
2hub2xvZ3kvMjAyMi9vY3QvMDEvZWxvbi1tdXNrLWFuZC10d2l0dGVyLWJvc3MtcGFyYWctYWdy=
YXdhbC1tZXNzYWdlcy1zaG93LWJsb3Nzb21pbmctcmVsYXRpb25zaGlw/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB0a0e6db9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">texting Agrawal</a>=C2=A0huffily to say =E2=80=9Cw=
hat did you get done this week=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cthis is a waste of tim=
e.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Musk offered to pay $54.20 per share, in c=
ash, for Twitter, which was significantly higher than the stock price at th=
e time. Agrawal could have said =E2=80=9Cno, no, we have a long-term value =
creation plan that will be worth far more than $54.20 per share, so we must=
 fight off Elon Musk and preserve the company=E2=80=99s independence, for s=
hareholders.=E2=80=9D Perhaps, as CEO, he could have persuaded the board of=
 directors to back that approach. Perhaps he could have sold that plan to s=
hareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0or perhaps he could have just used a <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34575923.258370/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMTgvdHdpdHRlci1oYXMt=
YS1wb2lzb24tcGlsbC1ub3c_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMwNTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1=
lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMzA1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj=
1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB712c5913" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  poison pill</a>=
 and other takeover-defense tools to frustrate Musk as much as possible.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Perhaps that would have=C2=A0<em>worked:</em> =
Perhaps Agrawal could have slowed down the deal process enough that Musk wo=
uld change his mind, either because he generally has a short attention span=
 or <em>because social-media company valuations fell in the spring of 2022<=
/em> and his bid for Twitter quickly became a bad idea. That would have bee=
n good for Agrawal: He could have kept running the company, getting paid an=
d having a nice time. It would have been=C2=A0<em>very bad=C2=A0</em>for Tw=
itter shareholders: They would have missed out on $54.20 per share, and the=
y=E2=80=99d be stuck holding Twitter stock as social-media valuations fell.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But, nope: Agrawal and Twitter=E2=80=99s board=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34575923.258370/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMDIvdHdp=
dHRlci1zLWJvYXJkLWdhdmUtdXA_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMwNTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl=
1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMzA1JnV0bV9jYW1wYW=
lnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1933d222" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  rapidly cap=
itulated</a>, with Agrawal giving employees a pretty unstirring speech abou=
t how the board had no choice but to take the best deal for shareholders. S=
o they signed a merger agreement to sell the company to Musk for $54.20 per=
 share.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then Musk tried to get out of it! A few mo=
nths later, after social-media valuations=C2=A0<em>did=C2=A0</em>fall, Musk=
=C2=A0<em>did=C2=A0</em>change his mind, and he sent Twitter a letter <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34575923.258370/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDctMDkvZWxvbi1zLW=
91dD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzA1MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY=
2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAzMDUmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1e56c86a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  saying he was terminating the deal=
</a>! Which would have been a catastrophe for Twitter shareholders =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0who would be stuck holding Twitter stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0but would =
have been =E2=80=A6=C2=A0kind of nice for Agrawal? Keep his job, keep his p=
aycheck, keep running Twitter, get a chance to turn things around without m=
eddling from Musk?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He could have done that! He could have sent Mu=
sk back a letter saying =E2=80=9Csorry you feel that way Elon, but we=E2=80=
=99d never force you to close a deal you don=E2=80=99t want to close, so, b=
ye.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-=
color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> Move on with his life, as Twitter CEO.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But, nope again:=C2=A0Agrawal, and Twitter=E2=
=80=99s board and executive team, hired lawyers and sued Musk and argued th=
at he had to close the deal, and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/34575923.258370/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9u=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDctMTgvZWxvbi13YW50cy10by1maWdodC10aGUtYm90cz9jbXBpZD1=
CQkQwMzA1MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldH=
RlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAzMDUmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB06097337" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">
of course they were right</a>, and ultimately Musk gave up and closed the d=
eal. And Twitter=E2=80=99s shareholders got their $54.20, which was a great=
 result for them under the circumstances. And Agrawal and his executive tea=
m got fired, which was an=C2=A0<em>absolutely inevitable=C2=A0</em>result f=
or them under the circumstances: They were the executives of the target in =
a hostile takeover, so they were going to get fired anyway, but also they r=
amped up the hostility of the takeover by=C2=A0<em>suing the acquirer to fo=
rce him to close</em>, so of course they got=C2=A0<em>extra=C2=A0</em>fired=
.=C2=A0Musk was mad at them! For making him buy Twitter!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My point here is that few CEOs have ever deser=
ved their severance package more than Parag Agrawal. This is not a commenta=
ry on his performance running Twitter:=C2=A0<em>That=C2=A0</em>performance =
was, you know, bad enough that Elon Musk bought the company. But a severanc=
e package is not a reward for good performance as CEO! A severance package =
is a reward for=C2=A0<em>getting out of the way</em>=C2=A0and letting someo=
ne else take over. And few CEOs have worked harder, or had a more unpleasan=
t time, getting out of the way. He earned his millions.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But then Musk didn=E2=80=99t pay him, <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34575923.258370/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDMtMDQvZXgtdHdpdHRlci1l=
eGVjdXRpdmVzLXN1ZS1tdXNrLWZvci0xMjgtbWlsbGlvbi1pbi1zZXZlcmFuY2UtcGF5P2NtcGl=
kPUJCRDAzMDUyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbG=
V0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDMwNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cBc3bde915" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  so he=E2=80=99s suing</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Four ex-Twitter executives, including former C=
hief Executive Officer Parag Agrawal, sued company owner Elon Musk for alle=
gedly stiffing them on more than $128 million in severance payments after t=
hey were ousted from the company.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The former top officials said Musk showed =E2=
=80=9Cspecial ire=E2=80=9D toward them after he took over the social-media =
platform in 2022, publicly vowing to withhold their severance to recoup abo=
ut $200 million from the $44 billion deal, according to a lawsuit filed Mon=
day in federal court in northern California.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Twitter, which Musk renamed X, has been accuse=
d in multiple suits of numerous labor and workplace violations, including f=
ailing to pay severance to thousands of workers laid off in the months afte=
r the takeover. The company also was accused in a raft of suits of failing =
to pay millions owed to vendors and landlords while purportedly trying to s=
tay financially solvent.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CUnder Musk=E2=80=99s control, Twitter=
 has become a scofflaw, stiffing employees, landlords, vendors, and others.=
 Musk doesn=E2=80=99t pay his bills, believes the rules don=E2=80=99t apply=
 to him, and uses his wealth and power to run roughshod over anyone who dis=
agrees with him,=E2=80=9D lawyers for Agrawal and the other ex-executives s=
aid in the 38-page complaint.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/34575923.258370/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVu=
dHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JxalgyODhFUGNzVS92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B1a563fab" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> the complaint</a>. Agrawal and the other executives =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0former Chief Financial Officer Ned Segal, Chief Legal Officer V=
ijaya Gadde and General Counsel Sean Edgett =E2=80=94=C2=A0had severance de=
als entitling them to get paid if Twitter was taken over and they were term=
inated =E2=80=9Cwithout cause.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9C=E2=80=98Cause=E2=80=99=C2=
=A0under the severance plans is limited to extremely narrow circumstances, =
such as being convicted of a felony or committing =E2=80=98gross negligence=
=E2=80=99=C2=A0or =E2=80=98willful misconduct.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D Musk fired=
 them immediately after the takeover =E2=80=94=C2=A0racing to fire them bef=
ore they could resign and get severance =E2=80=94=C2=A0and claimed it was f=
or =E2=80=9Ccause.=E2=80=9D The supposed =E2=80=9Ccause=E2=80=9D was things=
 like the executives paying lawyers to sue Musk to make him close the deal,=
 which Musk argued was a waste of corporate resources. That is not how seve=
rance is supposed to work! The complaint says:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Severance plans are an important f=
eature of modern corporate governance, aligning the economic interests of e=
xecutives and shareholders in the face of a corporate takeover, especially =
one as contentious as Musk=E2=80=99s acquisition of Twitter. Severance plan=
s encourage=C2=A0everyone to work toward getting the deal done. For example=
, without severance plans, executives could have a financial incentive to o=
ppose an acquisition even when that acquisition is in the best interests of=
 shareholders. Executives could also have a professional incentive to leave=
 the company before the closing, which could jeopardize the company=E2=80=
=99s ability to close the transaction and the public shareholders=E2=80=99 =
ability to get the control premium provided by the acquisition. Executives=
=E2=80=99 severance benefits are designed to be legally resilient, as they =
must be, because severance payments are necessarily made by the acquired en=
tity only after it passes into the hands of its acquiror. If executives cou=
ld not count on getting their contractual severance, they would have no inc=
entive to stay through the acquisition to run the business, oversee the acq=
uisition process, and make sure the shareholders get paid.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The problem is that Twitter=E2=80=99s old exec=
utives were working on behalf of its old public shareholders, and they got =
a good deal for those shareholders. But to do that, they had to work=C2=A0<=
em>against=C2=A0</em>its new owner, Musk, so they got=C2=A0<em>him=C2=A0</e=
m>a bad deal. And the public shareholders agreed to the severance package, =
but Musk has to pay it. Of course he doesn=E2=80=99t want to!</p>
