<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have talked a couple of times recently abou=
t BOXX, the Alpha Architect 1-3 Month Box ETF, an=C2=A0exchange-traded fund=
 that is meant to pay roughly Treasury bill interest rates without taxes. T=
he <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34575923.258370=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDItMjIvcH=
V0LXRoZS1tb25leS1pbi10aGUtYm94eD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzA1MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fb=
WVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAzMDUmdXRtX2Nh=
bXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB22e04418" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">first ti=
me</a> we discussed it, I laid out how it=E2=80=99s supposed to work, basic=
ally by converting interest (taxed at ordinary income rates) into capital g=
ains (taxed at favorable rates), and then by using ETF technology to defer =
those capital gains until the holder sells out of the fund.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/34575923.258370/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9u=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDItMjYvaG9uZXktaS1pbnNpZGVyLXRyYWRlZC15b3VyLW1lcmdlcj9=
jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzA1MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bm=
V3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAzMDUmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB99799578" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;">second time</a> we discussed it, it was b=
ecause several readers argued that that actually doesn=E2=80=99t work, that=
 the US tax code has provisions to prevent that sort of conversion of inter=
est income into capital gains. Specifically, the tax code <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34575923.258370/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF=
3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L3VzY29kZS90ZXh0LzI2LzEyNTg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0fbbc=
a38" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">has a provision</a> covering =E2=80=9Cconversions,=E2=80=9D a =
tax term referring to buying things (stocks, etc.) and selling them forward=
 simultaneously. Buying stock and selling it forward gets rid of your stock=
-price risk and leaves you with only a risk-free investment for some period=
 of time, which should pay roughly the risk-free interest rate. It turns in=
terest income (you put in money, you get paid for locking it up) into capit=
al gains (you buy a stock, you sell it later at a higher price). But then t=
he conversion rules turn those capital gains=C2=A0<em>back=C2=A0</em>into i=
nterest income; they say =E2=80=9Cnah, that=E2=80=99s too cute, that's inte=
rest.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Are BOXX=E2=80=99s trades conversions? I don=
=E2=80=99t know, but here is Steven Rosenthal <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/34575923.258370/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGF4cG9saWN5Y2V=
udGVyLm9yZy90YXh2b3gvdGF4LWdpbW1pY2stYm94eA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3eb2d2=
7f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">arguing yes</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Earning interest-equivalent income while payin=
g capital-gains taxes is especially alluring today, with short-term interes=
t rates near a 20-year high. But, despite its popularity, BOXX violates bot=
h the letter and the spirit of the anti-conversion statute.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Referring to the first of the controlling stat=
ute=E2=80=99s two-part test, substantially all of the shareholders=E2=80=99=
 expected return is attributable to the time value of their net investment.=
 There is no question the shareholders expect an interest-like return on th=
eir purchase of BOXX shares.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am torn. On the one hand, I still think that=
, conceptually, it=C2=A0<em>should=C2=A0</em>be possible to turn interest i=
nto capital gains: All capital gains are in some sense compensation for loc=
king up your money in some asset, there is no sharp distinction between app=
reciation and interest, and it just feels like a good field for financial e=
ngineering. On the other hand, right, =E2=80=9Cwe pay you Treasury interest=
 without taxes=E2=80=9D does seem a bit too good to be true.</p>
